03959nam a22004935i 9780822384441DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223844417 a10.1515/97808223844412doi  a(DE-B1597)552692  a(OCoLC)1055290378  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aEDU0400002bisacsh1 aDávila, Jerry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiploma of Whiteness :bRace and Social Policy in Brazil, 1917-1945 /cJerry Dávila. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (305 p.) :b41 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Building the ''Brazilian Man -- t2. Educating Brazil -- t3. What Happened to Rio's Teachers of Color? -- t4. Elementary Education -- t5. Escola Nova no Estado Novo: The New School in the New State -- t6. Behaving White: Rio's Secondary Schools -- tEpilogue: The Enduring Brazilian Fascination with Race -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Brazil, the country with the largest population of African descent in the Americas, the idea of race underwent a dramatic shift in the first half of the twentieth century. Brazilian authorities, who had considered race a biological fact, began to view it as a cultural and environmental condition. Jerry Dávila explores the significance of this transition by looking at the history of the Rio de Janeiro school system between 1917 and 1945. He demonstrates how, in the period between the world wars, the dramatic proliferation of social policy initiatives in Brazil was subtly but powerfully shaped by beliefs that racially mixed and nonwhite Brazilians could be symbolically, if not physically, whitened through changes in culture, habits, and health.Providing a unique historical perspective on how racial attitudes move from elite discourse into people's lives, Diploma of Whiteness shows how public schools promoted the idea that whites were inherently fit and those of African or mixed ancestry were necessarily in need of remedial attention. Analyzing primary material-including school system records, teacher journals, photographs, private letters, and unpublished documents-Dávila traces the emergence of racially coded hiring practices and student-tracking policies as well as the development of a social and scientific philosophy of eugenics. He contends that the implementation of the various policies intended to "improve" nonwhites institutionalized subtle barriers to their equitable integration into Brazilian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384441zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822384441.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles